The question then arises whether it is more probable that Horace should have employed a phrase nowhere else found, and extremely hard to explain by the usage of the language, or that an error of one slight stroke should have crept into the archetype. When we consider passages like 1. 5. 283 7. 96; Epod. 1. 153 4. 83 S. 1. 6. 102; 10. 86, 130 take only cases where the archetype was unquestionably corrupt, we can hardly hesitate which way We should decide.
